# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: information-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] In mathematics, specifically statistics and information geometry, a **Bregman divergence** or **Bregman distance** is a measure of difference between two points, defined in terms of a strictly convex function; they form an important class of divergences.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] When the points are interpreted as probability distributions – notably as either values of the parameter of a parametric model or as a data set of observed values – the resulting distance is a statistical distance.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] The most basic Bregman divergence is the squared Euclidean distance.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences are similar to metrics, but satisfy neither the triangle inequality (ever) nor symmetry (in general).
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] However, they satisfy a generalization of the Pythagorean theorem, and in information geometry the corresponding statistical manifold is interpreted as a (dually) flat manifold.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] This allows many techniques of optimization theory to be generalized to Bregman divergences, geometrically as generalizations of least squares.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences are named after Soviet and Israeli mathematician Lev M.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman, who introduced the concept in 1967.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Let $F\colon \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ be a continuously-differentiable, strictly convex function defined on a convex set $\Omega$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Then $g'(t)=\langle \nabla f(z(t)),v\rangle$ for $t\in (0,r)$ , and since $\nabla f$ is continuous, also for $t=0,r$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Thus we find that $\nabla f$ varies linearly along any direction.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Since f is also strictly convex, it is of form $f(x)+x^{T}Ax+B^{T}x+C$ , where $A\succ 0$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Proof idea: For any quadratic function $q:S\to \mathbb {R}$ , we have $f-q$ still has such derivative-linearity, so we will subtract away a few quadratic functions and show that f becomes zero.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] The proof idea can be illustrated fully for the case of $S=\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , so we prove it in this case.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] By the derivative-linearity, f is a quadratic function on any line segment in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] We subtract away four quadratic functions, such that $g:=f-q_{0}-q_{1}-q_{2}-q_{3}$ becomes identically zero on the x-axis, y-axis, and the $\{x=y\}$ line.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Now use $q_{0}$ to remove the linear term, and use $q_{1},q_{2},q_{3}$ respectively to remove the quadratic terms along the three lines.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] $\forall (x,y)\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ not on the origin, there exists a line l across $(x,y)$ that intersects the x-axis, y-axis, and the $\{x=y\}$ line at three different points.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Since g is quadratic on l , and is zero on three different points, g is identically zero on l , thus $g(x,y)=0$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] The following two characterizations are for divergences on $\Gamma _{n}$ , the set of all probability measures on $\{1,2,...,n\}$ , with $n\geq 2$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Given a Bregman divergence $D_{F}$ , its "opposite", defined by $D_{F}^{*}(v,w)=D_{F}(w,v)$ , is generally not a Bregman divergence.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] For example, the Kullback-Leiber divergence is both a Bregman divergence and an f-divergence.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Its reverse is also an f-divergence, but by the above characterization, the reverse KL divergence cannot be a Bregman divergence.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] A key tool in computational geometry is the idea of projective duality, which maps points to hyperplanes and vice versa, while preserving incidence and above-below relationships.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] There are numerous analytical forms of the projective dual: one common form maps the point $p=(p_{1},\ldots p_{d})$ to the hyperplane ${\textstyle x_{d+1}=\sum _{i=1}^{d}2p_{i}x_{i}}$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] This mapping can be interpreted (identifying the hyperplane with its normal) as the convex conjugate mapping that takes the point p to its dual point $p^{*}=\nabla F(p)$ , where *F* defines the *d*-dimensional paraboloid ${\textstyle x_{d+1}=\sum _{i}x_{i}^{2}}$ .
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] If we now replace the paraboloid by an arbitrary convex function, we obtain a different dual mapping that retains the incidence and above-below properties of the standard projective dual.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] This implies that natural dual concepts in computational geometry like Voronoi diagrams and Delaunay triangulations retain their meaning in distance spaces defined by an arbitrary Bregman divergence.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences can be interpreted as limit cases of skewed Jensen divergences (see Nielsen and Boltz, 2011).
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Jensen divergences can be generalized using comparative convexity, and limit cases of these skewed Jensen divergences generalizations yields generalized Bregman divergence (see Nielsen and Nock, 2017).
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] The Bregman chord divergence is obtained by taking a chord instead of a tangent line.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences can also be defined between matrices, between functions, and between measures (distributions).
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences between matrices include the Stein's loss and von Neumann entropy.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergences between functions include total squared error, relative entropy, and squared bias; see the references by Frigyik et al. below for definitions and properties.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Similarly Bregman divergences have also been defined over sets, through a submodular set function which is known as the discrete analog of a convex function.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] For a list of common matrix Bregman divergences, see Table 15.1 in.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] In machine learning, Bregman divergences are used to calculate the bi-tempered logistic loss, performing better than the softmax function with noisy datasets.
[src:information-geometry/bregman-divergence] Bregman divergence is used in the formulation of mirror descent, which includes optimization algorithms used in machine learning such as gradient descent and the hedge algorithm.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] In estimation theory and statistics, the **Cramér–Rao bound** (**CRB**) relates to estimation of a deterministic (fixed, though unknown) parameter.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] The result is named in honor of Harald Cramér and Calyampudi Radhakrishna Rao, but has also been derived independently by Maurice Fréchet, Georges Darmois, and by Alexander Aitken and Harold Silverstone.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] It is also known as Fréchet–Cramér–Rao or Fréchet–Darmois–Cramér–Rao lower bound.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] It states that the precision of any unbiased estimator is at most the Fisher information; or (equivalently) the reciprocal of the Fisher information is a lower bound on its variance.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] An unbiased estimator that achieves this bound is said to be (fully) *efficient*.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] Such a solution achieves the lowest possible mean squared error among all unbiased methods, and is, therefore, the minimum variance unbiased (MVU) estimator.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] However, in some cases, no unbiased technique exists which achieves the bound.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] This may occur either if for any unbiased estimator, there exists another with a strictly smaller variance, or if an MVU estimator exists, but its variance is strictly greater than the inverse of the Fisher information.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] The Cramér–Rao bound can also be used to bound the variance of *biased* estimators of given bias.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] In some cases, a biased approach can result in both a variance and a mean squared error that are *below* the unbiased Cramér–Rao lower bound; see estimator bias.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] Significant progress over the Cramér–Rao lower bound was proposed by Anil Kumar Bhattacharyya through a series of works, called Bhattacharyya bound.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] The Cramér–Rao bound is stated in this section for several increasingly general cases, beginning with the case in which the parameter is a scalar and its estimator is unbiased.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] All versions of the bound require certain regularity conditions, which hold for most well-behaved distributions.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] These conditions are listed later in this section.
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] Suppose $\theta$ is an unknown deterministic parameter that is to be estimated from n independent observations (measurements) of x , each from a distribution according to some probability density function $f(x;\theta )$ .
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] and $\ell (x;\theta )=\log(f(x;\theta ))$ is the natural logarithm of the likelihood function for a single sample x and $\operatorname {E} _{x;\theta }$ denotes the expected value with respect to the density $f(x;\theta )$ of X .
[src:information-geometry/cramér-rao-bound] If not indicated, in what follows, the expectation is taken with respect to X .
