[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] In information geometry, a **divergence** is a kind of statistical distance: a binary function which establishes the separation from one probability distribution to another on a statistical manifold.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The simplest divergence is squared Euclidean distance (SED), and divergences can be viewed as generalizations of SED.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The other most important divergence is relative entropy (also called Kullback–Leibler divergence), which is central to information theory.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] There are numerous other specific divergences and classes of divergences, notably *f*-divergences and Bregman divergences (see § Examples).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] At every point $p\in M$ , $D(p,p+dp)$ is a positive-definite quadratic form for infinitesimal displacements $dp$ from p .
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] In applications to statistics, the manifold M is typically the space of parameters of a parametric family of probability distributions.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Condition 3 means that D defines an inner product on the tangent space $T_{p}M$ for every $p\in M$ .
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Since D is $C^{2}$ on M , this defines a Riemannian metric g on M .
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Locally at $p\in M$ , we may construct a local coordinate chart with coordinates x , then the divergence is $D(x(p),x(p)+dx)=\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}dx^{T}g_{p}(x)dx+O(|dx|^{3})$ where $g_{p}(x)$ is a matrix of size $n\times n$ .
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] It is the Riemannian metric at point p expressed in coordinates x .
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Dimensional analysis of condition 3 shows that divergence has the dimension of squared distance.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] When we wish to contrast D against $D^{*}$ , we refer to D as **primal divergence**.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Unlike metrics, divergences are not required to be symmetric, and the asymmetry is important in applications.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Accordingly, one often refers asymmetrically to the divergence "of *q* from *p*" or "from *p* to *q*", rather than "between *p* and *q*".
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Secondly, divergences generalize *squared* distance, not linear distance, and thus do not satisfy the triangle inequality, but some divergences (such as the Bregman divergence) do satisfy generalizations of the Pythagorean theorem.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] In general statistics and probability, "divergence" generally refers to any kind of function $D(p,q)$ , where $p,q$ are probability distributions or other objects under consideration, such that conditions 1, 2 are satisfied.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Condition 3 is required for "divergence" as used in information geometry.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] As an example, the total variation distance, a commonly used statistical divergence, does not satisfy condition 3.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Notation for divergences varies significantly between fields, though there are some conventions.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Divergences are generally notated with an uppercase 'D', as in $D(x,y)$ , to distinguish them from metric distances, which are notated with a lowercase 'd'.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] When multiple divergences are in use, they are commonly distinguished with subscripts, as in $D_{\text{KL}}$ for Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL divergence).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Often a different separator between parameters is used, particularly to emphasize the asymmetry.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] A colon may be used instead, as $D(p:q)$ ; this emphasizes the relative information supporting the two distributions.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The notation for parameters varies as well.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Uppercase $P,Q$ interprets the parameters as probability distributions, while lowercase $p,q$ or $x,y$ interprets them geometrically as points in a space, and $\mu _{1},\mu _{2}$ or $m_{1},m_{2}$ interprets them as measures.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Many properties of divergences can be derived if we restrict *S* to be a statistical manifold, meaning that it can be parametrized with a finite-dimensional coordinate system *θ*, so that for a distribution *p* ∈ *S* we can write *p* = *p*(*θ*).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] where matrix *g*(*D*) is positive semi-definite and defines a unique Riemannian metric on the manifold *S*.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] and the dual to this connection ∇* is generated by the dual divergence *D**.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Thus, a divergence *D*(·, ·) generates on a statistical manifold a unique dualistic structure (*g*(*D*), ∇(*D*), ∇(*D**)).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The converse is also true: every torsion-free dualistic structure on a statistical manifold is induced from some globally defined divergence function (which however need not be unique).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] For example, when *D* is an f-divergence for some function ƒ(·), then it generates the metric *g*(*D**f*) = *c·g* and the connection ∇(*D**f*) = ∇(*α*), where *g* is the canonical Fisher information metric, ∇(*α*) is the α-connection, *c* = ƒ′′(1), and *α* = 3 + 2ƒ′′′(1)/ƒ′′(1).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The two most important divergences are the relative entropy (Kullback–Leibler divergence, KL divergence), which is central to information theory and statistics, and the squared Euclidean distance (SED).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Minimizing these two divergences is the main way that linear inverse problems are solved, via the principle of maximum entropy and least squares, notably in logistic regression and linear regression.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The two most important classes of divergences are the *f*-divergences and Bregman divergences; however, other types of divergence functions are also encountered in the literature.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The only divergence for probabilities over a finite alphabet that is both an *f*-divergence and a Bregman divergence is the Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The squared Euclidean divergence is a Bregman divergence (corresponding to the function ⁠ $x^{2}$ ⁠) but not an *f*-divergence.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Bregman divergences correspond to convex functions on convex sets.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The dual divergence to a Bregman divergence is the divergence generated by the convex conjugate *F** of the Bregman generator of the original divergence.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] For example, for the squared Euclidean distance, the generator is ⁠ $x^{2}$ ⁠, while for the relative entropy the generator is the negative entropy ⁠ $x\log x$ ⁠.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The use of the term "divergence" – both what functions it refers to, and what various statistical distances are called – has varied significantly over time, but by c.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] 2000 had settled on the current usage within information geometry, notably in the textbook Amari & Nagaoka (2000).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The term "divergence" for a statistical distance was used informally in various contexts from c.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The term was popularized by its use for the Kullback–Leibler divergence in Kullback & Leibler (1951) and its use in the textbook Kullback (1959).
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The term "divergence" was used generally by Ali & Silvey (1966) for statistically distances.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Numerous references to earlier uses of statistical distances are given in Adhikari & Joshi (1956) and Kullback (1959, pp.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The information geometry definition of divergence (the subject of this article) was initially referred to by alternative terms, including "quasi-distance" Amari (1982, p.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] 369) and "contrast function" Eguchi (1985), though "divergence" was used in Amari (1985) for the *α*-divergence, and has become standard for the general class.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] The term "divergence" is in contrast to a distance (metric), since the symmetrized divergence does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] For example, the term "Bregman distance" is still found, but "Bregman divergence" is now preferred.
[src:information-geometry/divergence-statistics] Notationally, Kullback & Leibler (1951) denoted their asymmetric function as $I(1:2)$ , while Ali & Silvey (1966) denote their functions with a lowercase 'd' as $d\left(P_{1},P_{2}\right)$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] In information geometry, the **Fisher information metric** is a particular Riemannian metric which can be defined on a smooth statistical manifold, *i.e.*, a smooth manifold whose points are probability distributions.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] It can be used to calculate the distance between probability distributions.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The metric is interesting in several aspects.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] By Chentsov's theorem, the Fisher information metric on statistical models is the only Riemannian metric (up to rescaling) that is invariant under sufficient statistics.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] It can also be understood to be the infinitesimal form of the relative entropy (*i.e.*, the Kullback–Leibler divergence); specifically, it is the Hessian of the divergence.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Alternately, it can be understood as the metric induced by the flat space Euclidean metric, after appropriate changes of variable.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] When pulled back to a complex projective Hilbert space, it becomes the Fubini–Study metric; when written in terms of mixed states, it is the quantum Bures metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Considered purely as a matrix, it is known as the Fisher information matrix.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Considered as a measurement technique, where it is used to estimate hidden parameters in terms of observed random variables, it is known as the observed information.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Given a statistical manifold with coordinates $\theta =(\theta _{1},\theta _{2},\ldots ,\theta _{n})$ , one writes $p(x\mid \theta )$ for the likelihood, that is the probability density of x as a function of $\theta$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Here x is drawn from the value space *R* for a (discrete or continuous) random variable *X*.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The integral is performed over all values *x* in *R*.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The variable $\theta$ is now a coordinate on a Riemann manifold.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The labels *j* and *k* index the local coordinate axes on the manifold.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] When the probability is derived from the Gibbs measure, as it would be for any Markovian process, then $\theta$ can also be understood to be a Lagrange multiplier; Lagrange multipliers are used to enforce constraints, such as holding the expectation value of some quantity constant.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] If there are *n* constraints holding *n* different expectation values constant, then the dimension of the manifold is *n* dimensions smaller than the original space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] In this case, the metric can be explicitly derived from the partition function; a derivation and discussion is presented there.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] and apply ${\frac {\partial }{\partial \theta _{k}}}$ on both sides.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] In this case, $\eta (\theta )=\theta$ , so the metric is just $\nabla _{\theta }^{2}A$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The metric diagonalizes to a mean part and a precision/variance part, that is, $g_{\mu ,\Sigma }=0$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This is because $\partial _{\Sigma }(\partial _{\mu }\ln p(x|\mu ,\Sigma ))$ is the product of $(x-\mu )$ with a term that depends only on $\Sigma$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] An approximate expression can be derived for a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The shortest paths (geodesics) between two univariate normal distributions are either parallel to the $\sigma$ axis, or half circular arcs centered on the $\mu /{\sqrt {2}}$ -axis.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Alternatively, the metric can be obtained as the second derivative of the *relative entropy* or Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] with $\Delta \theta ^{j}$ an infinitesimally small change of $\theta$ in the *j* direction.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The symmetric matrix $g_{jk}$ is positive (semi) definite and is the Hessian matrix of the function $f_{\theta _{0}}(\theta )$ at the extremum point $\theta _{0}$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Intuitively, this states that the distance between two infinitesimally close points on a statistical differential manifold is the informational difference between them.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The Ruppeiner metric and Weinhold metric are the Fisher information metric calculated for Gibbs distributions as the ones found in equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The path parameter here is time *t*; this action can be understood to give the change in free entropy of a system as it is moved from time *a* to time *b*.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This observation has resulted in practical applications in chemical and processing industry: in order to minimize the change in free entropy of a system, one should follow the minimum geodesic path between the desired endpoints of the process.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The geodesic minimizes the entropy, due to the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, which states that the action is bounded below by the length of the curve, squared.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The Fisher metric also allows the action and the curve length to be related to the Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] where the integrand *dJSD* is understood to be the infinitesimal change in the Jensen–Shannon divergence along the path taken.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] That is, the square root of the Jensen–Shannon divergence is just the Fisher metric (divided by the square root of 8).
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] For a discrete probability space, that is, a probability space on a finite set of objects, the Fisher metric can be understood to simply be the Euclidean metric restricted to a positive orthant (e.g.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] "quadrant" in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ) of a unit sphere, after appropriate changes of variable.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Consider a flat, Euclidean space, of dimension *N*+1, parametrized by points $y=(y_{0},\cdots ,y_{n})$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] where the $\textstyle dy_{i}$ are 1-forms; they are the basis vectors for the cotangent space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The superscript 'flat' is there to remind that, when written in coordinate form, this metric is with respect to the flat-space coordinate y .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This embedding induces a metric on the sphere, it is inherited directly from the Euclidean metric on the ambient space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] It takes exactly the same form as the above, taking care to ensure that the coordinates are constrained to lie on the surface of the sphere.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This can be done, e.g. with the technique of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Consider now the change of variable $p_{i}=y_{i}^{2}$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The last can be recognized as one-fourth of the Fisher information metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] To complete the process, recall that the probabilities are parametric functions of the manifold variables $\theta$ , that is, one has $p_{i}=p_{i}(\theta )$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The superscript 'fisher' is present to remind that this expression is applicable for the coordinates $\theta$ ; whereas the non-coordinate form is the same as the Euclidean (flat-space) metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] That is, the Fisher information metric on a statistical manifold is simply (four times) the Euclidean metric restricted to the positive orthant of the sphere, after appropriate changes of variable.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] When the random variable p is not discrete, but continuous, the argument still holds.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This can be seen in one of two different ways.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] One way is to carefully recast all of the above steps in an infinite-dimensional space, being careful to define limits appropriately, etc., in order to make sure that all manipulations are well-defined, convergent, etc.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The other way, as noted by Gromov, is to use a category-theoretic approach; that is, to note that the above manipulations remain valid in the category of probabilities.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Here such a category would have the Radon–Nikodym property, that is, the Radon–Nikodym theorem holds in this category.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This includes the Hilbert spaces; these are square-integrable, and in the manipulations above, this is sufficient to safely replace the sum over squares by an integral over squares.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The above manipulations deriving the Fisher metric from the Euclidean metric can be extended to complex projective Hilbert spaces.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] In this case, one obtains the Fubini–Study metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This should perhaps be no surprise, as the Fubini–Study metric provides the means of measuring information in quantum mechanics.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The Bures metric, also known as the Helstrom metric, is identical to the Fubini–Study metric, although the latter is usually written in terms of pure states, as below, whereas the Bures metric is written for mixed states.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] By setting the phase of the complex coordinate to zero, one obtains exactly one-fourth of the Fisher information metric, exactly as above.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Here, $\psi (x;\theta )$ is a complex-valued probability amplitude; $p(x;\theta )$ and $\alpha (x;\theta )$ are strictly real.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The previous calculations are obtained by setting $\alpha (x;\theta )=0$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] When $\psi (x;\theta )$ is real, this is the surface of a sphere.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The expression $\vert \delta \psi \rangle$ can be understood to be an infinitesimal variation; equivalently, it can be understood to be a 1-form in the cotangent space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Setting $\delta \alpha =0$ in the above makes it clear that the first term is (one-fourth of) the Fisher information metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The full form of the above can be made slightly clearer by changing notation to that of standard Riemannian geometry, so that the metric becomes a symmetric 2-form acting on the tangent space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The imaginary term is a symplectic form, it is the Berry phase or geometric phase.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Again, the first term can be clearly seen to be (one fourth of) the Fisher information metric, by setting $\alpha =0$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Equivalently, the Fubini–Study metric can be understood as the metric on complex projective Hilbert space that is induced by the complex extension of the flat Euclidean metric.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The difference between this, and the Bures metric, is that the Bures metric is written in terms of mixed states.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] A slightly more formal, abstract definition can be given, as follows.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Let *X* be an orientable manifold, and let $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ be a measure on *X*.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Equivalently, let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ be a probability space on $\Omega =X$ , with sigma algebra ${\mathcal {F}}=\Sigma$ and probability $P=\mu$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The statistical manifold *S*(*X*) of *X* is defined as the space of all measures $\mu$ on *X* (with the sigma-algebra $\Sigma$ held fixed).
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Note that this space is infinite-dimensional, and is commonly taken to be a Fréchet space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Pick a point $\mu \in S(X)$ and consider the tangent space $T_{\mu }S$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The Fisher information metric is then an inner product on the tangent space.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] The abuse of notation is to write the tangent vectors as if they are derivatives, and to insert the extraneous *d* in writing the integral: the integration is meant to be carried out using the measure $\mu$ over the whole space *X*.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This abuse of notation is, in fact, taken to be perfectly normal in measure theory; it is the standard notation for the Radon–Nikodym derivative.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] In order for the integral to be well-defined, the space *S*(*X*) must have the Radon–Nikodym property, and more specifically, the tangent space is restricted to those vectors that are square-integrable.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Square integrability is equivalent to saying that a Cauchy sequence converges to a finite value under the weak topology: the space contains its limit points.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Note that Hilbert spaces possess this property.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] This definition of the metric can be seen to be equivalent to the previous, in several steps.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] First, one selects a submanifold of *S*(*X*) by considering only those measures $\mu$ that are parameterized by some smoothly varying parameter $\theta$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Then, if $\theta$ is finite-dimensional, then so is the submanifold; likewise, the tangent space has the same dimension as $\theta$ .
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] With some additional abuse of language, one notes that the exponential map provides a map from vectors in a tangent space to points in an underlying manifold.
[src:information-geometry/fisher-information-metric] Thus, one has the appearance of logarithms in the simpler definition, previously given.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] Historically, information geometry can be traced back to the work of C.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] Rao, who was the first to treat the Fisher matrix as a Riemannian metric.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] The modern theory is largely due to Shun'ichi Amari, whose work has been greatly influential on the development of the field.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] Classically, information geometry considered a parametrized statistical model as a Riemannian, conjugate connection, statistical, and dually flat manifolds.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] Unlike usual smooth manifolds with tensor metric and Levi-Civita connection, these take into account conjugate connection, torsion, and Amari-Chentsov metric.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] All presented above geometric structures find application in information theory and machine learning.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] For such models, there is a natural choice of Riemannian metric, known as the Fisher information metric.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] In the special case that the statistical model is an exponential family, it is possible to induce the statistical manifold with a Hessian metric (i.e a Riemannian metric given by the potential of a convex function).
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] In this case, the manifold naturally inherits two flat affine connections, as well as a canonical Bregman divergence.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] Historically, much of the work was devoted to studying the associated geometry of these examples.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] In the modern setting, information geometry applies to a much wider context, including non-exponential families, nonparametric statistics, and even abstract statistical manifolds not induced from a known statistical model.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] The results combine techniques from information theory, affine differential geometry, convex analysis and many other fields.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] One of the most perspective information geometry approaches find applications in machine learning.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] For example, the developing of information-geometric optimization methods (mirror descent and natural gradient descent).
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] The standard references in the field are Shun’ichi Amari and Hiroshi Nagaoka's book, *Methods of Information Geometry*, and the more recent book by Nihat Ay and others.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] A gentle introduction is given in the survey by Frank Nielsen.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] In 2018, the journal *Information Geometry* was released, which is devoted to the field.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] The history of information geometry is associated with the discoveries of at least the following people, and many others.
[src:information-geometry/information-geometry] As an interdisciplinary field, information geometry has been used in various applications.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] In mathematics, a **statistical manifold** is a Riemannian manifold, each of whose points is a probability distribution.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Statistical manifolds provide a setting for the field of information geometry.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] The Fisher information metric provides a metric on these manifolds.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Following this definition, the log-likelihood function is a differentiable map and the score is an inclusion.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] The family of all normal distributions can be thought of as a 2-dimensional parametric space parametrized by the expected value *μ* and the variance *σ*2 ≥ 0.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Equipped with the Riemannian metric given by the Fisher information matrix, it is a statistical manifold with a geometry modeled on hyperbolic space.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] A way of picturing the manifold is done by inferring the parametric equations via the Fisher Information rather than starting from the likelihood-function.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] A simple example of a statistical manifold, taken from physics, would be the canonical ensemble: it is a one-dimensional manifold, with the temperature *T* serving as the coordinate on the manifold.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] For any fixed temperature *T*, one has a probability space: so, for a gas of atoms, it would be the probability distribution of the velocities of the atoms.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] As one varies the temperature *T*, the probability distribution varies.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Another simple example, taken from medicine, would be the probability distribution of patient outcomes, in response to the quantity of medicine administered.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] That is, for a fixed dose, some patients improve, and some do not: this is the base probability space.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] If the dosage is varied, then the probability of outcomes changes.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Thus, the dosage is the coordinate on the manifold.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] To be a smooth manifold, one would have to measure outcomes in response to arbitrarily small changes in dosage; this is not a practically realizable example, unless one has a pre-existing mathematical model of dose-response where the dose can be arbitrarily varied.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Note that this space is infinite-dimensional; it is commonly taken to be a Fréchet space.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] Rather than dealing with an infinite-dimensional space *S*(*X*), it is common to work with a finite-dimensional submanifold, defined by considering a set of probability distributions parameterized by some smooth, continuously varying parameter $\theta$ .
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] That is, one considers only those measures that are selected by the parameter.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] If the parameter $\theta$ is *n*-dimensional, then, in general, the submanifold will be as well.
[src:information-geometry/statistical-manifold] All finite-dimensional statistical manifolds can be understood in this way.
